                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     SPORT BRIEFS
                                                  Mendis joins Lanka squad  Dhaka: Sri Lankan spinner Ajantha Mendis joined the squad in Bangladesh on Monday after a quick recovery from an ankle injury that was expected to keep him out of the Test series. The Telegraph had reported on Sunday that this was likely to happen.
  Mendis, 23, suffered severe soft tissue damage in his right ankle during a domestic game early this month and was replaced by left-arm spinner Rangana Herath for the two-Test series.  ldquo;My ankle is alright now as I am feeling no pain, rdquo; Mendis told reporters on his arrival in Dhaka on Monday.  He is now expected to play in the second Test starting in Chittagong on Saturday.  ICC decision  Calcutta: A firmer and more practical anti-doping code has been approved for implementation by the International Cricket Council (ICC). The code, which comes into effect on January 1, 2009, was recently given unanimous approval by all members of the ICC Board.  Shukla urges  New Delhi: The ministry of sports decision to bar athletes with foreign passports from representing the country in international events contradicts the government policy on People of Indian Origin (PIO) and hence should be reconsidered, Rajya Sabha member Rajeev Shukla said here Monday.  Surya held  Mangalore: Surya Sekhar Ganguly is just a draw away from a record sixth successive national A title after splitting a point with S. Satyapragyan in the 11th and penultimate round of the 46th National A Chess Championship here Monday. Maharashtra rsquo;s Akshayraj Kore joined Ganguly at the top of the table with 7.5 points after stunning Grandmaster Parimarjan Negi in his last round match.  Chennai Open  New Delhi: Security will be tightened ahead of next week rsquo;s Chennai Open ATP tennis tournament following the militant attacks in Mumbai, a tournament official said on Monday. Independent security consultant Reg Dickason will inspect the venue in the southern city for the January 5-11 event and the players will receive a briefing.   Tirkey weds   Simdega (Jharkhand): In a marriage between two hockey players, former India captain Ignace Tirkey tied the knot with women rsquo;s team member Masira Surin at a church here Monday.   Dubious feat   London: A player with English minor league club Chippenham Town has set a record for the fastest-red card in senior soccer when he was sent off for a wild tackle three seconds after kick-off, British media reported on Monday.   
